insert into public.questions
  (id, parent_id, type, category, subtopic, importance, difficulty, candidate_level, region, question, key_points, model_answer)
values
(1905, NULL, 'primary', $x$Capital Markets$x$, $x$Setting The IPO Range$x$, 'core', 2, 'intern', 'Global', $x$When taking a company public, how do bankers actually arrive at the initial IPO price range that goes in the prospectus?$x$, $x$["Relative valuation vs listed peers", "Trading and transaction comps", "Apply IPO discount to fair value", "DCF as a cross-check", "Investor education / pilot fishing feedback", "Range wraps around anticipated demand", "Discount incentivizes subscription"]$x$::jsonb, $x$I start from where comparable listed companies trade, because public investors price a new issue relative to names they already own. I build a peer set, look at the multiples the market is paying - often forward EV/EBITDA or a sector-specific metric like EV/sales or P/E - and apply them to the issuer's forecast to get a fair-value anchor. I'll sanity-check that with a DCF and any recent transaction multiples. Then the key move is that I do not price at fair value; I apply an IPO discount, typically in the mid teens percent, so new investors are paid to take primary-market risk and the deal trades up. Before the range is fixed I gather feedback through early investor education and pilot fishing, sounding out a handful of key accounts on valuation. The published range is built to sit just below where I think real demand lives, so the book can build with momentum rather than stall. It is as much a marketing tool as a valuation output.$x$),
(1906, NULL, 'primary', $x$Capital Markets$x$, $x$Book-Building And Allocation$x$, 'standard', 3, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$During book-building for an IPO, how do you read the order book to set the final price, and how do you decide which investors get allocated?$x$, $x$["Demand curve by limit price", "Coverage and oversubscription multiple", "Quality vs price-sensitivity of orders", "Long-only anchors vs hedge-fund flippers", "Allocate for aftermarket stability", "Price below clearing to leave momentum", "Issuer sign-off on the book"]$x$::jsonb, $x$As orders come in I build a demand curve - how many shares are bid at each limit price - so I can see where the book clears and how oversubscribed it is at various levels. Coverage matters, but the composition matters more. I separate sticky long-only money and any cornerstones from fast-money hedge funds that are likely to flip on day one, and I look at how price-sensitive each order is. I usually price a touch below the absolute clearing level so the stock has room to trade up and reward the buyers I want to keep. On allocation, the book is discretionary in most jurisdictions: I tilt toward high-quality holders who will support the aftermarket and add to positions, scale back accounts I think will sell immediately, and reward investors who gave early price-supportive feedback or took the IPO risk. The issuer signs off on the final allocation. The goal is a stable shareholder register and a clean break above the IPO price, not just the highest headline price.$x$),
(1907, NULL, 'primary', $x$Capital Markets$x$, $x$Cornerstone Investors$x$, 'standard', 3, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$What is a cornerstone investor in an IPO, how does it differ from an anchor order, and what are the trade-offs of bringing one in?$x$, $x$["Cornerstone commits pre-launch with disclosure", "Guaranteed allocation and lock-up", "Anchor is early in-book, not pre-committed", "Validation and de-risks the trade", "Common in Asia / EMEA listings", "Cost is reduced free float and price discovery", "Signaling to other accounts"]$x$::jsonb, $x$A cornerstone is an investor who commits to a fixed dollar amount before the deal launches, gets a guaranteed allocation regardless of the final price, and is named in the prospectus, usually with a lock-up on those shares. That public commitment de-risks the transaction and signals quality to the rest of the market, which is why cornerstones are so common in Hong Kong and Middle East listings and increasingly in Europe for tougher deals. An anchor order is softer: it is a large, high-quality order placed early in the book to build momentum, but it is not pre-committed, not guaranteed, and not disclosed by name. The trade-off with cornerstones is that you give away price discovery - they take shares at whatever price the deal sets, so they are effectively short the upside and want a generous range - and you shrink the genuinely tradable free float, which can hurt aftermarket liquidity. So I use them to anchor confidence in a shaky window, but I am careful not to wrap up so much of the book that real price formation disappears.$x$),
(1908, NULL, 'primary', $x$Capital Markets$x$, $x$Lock-Up Expiry Dynamics$x$, 'standard', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$Explain IPO lock-ups and what tends to happen around expiry. As a banker, how would you manage a large expiry for a recently listed company?$x$, $x$["Typically 180-day restriction on insiders", "Prevents supply flood post-IPO", "Overhang and price weakness into expiry", "Magnitude depends on free float vs locked shares", "Underwriter can waive early", "Manage via staggered release or marketed block", "Pre-expiry communication to the market"]$x$::jsonb, $x$A lock-up is a contractual restriction, usually 180 days, stopping insiders, founders and pre-IPO holders from selling right after listing, so the small free float at IPO is not immediately swamped by supply. The problem is the expiry itself: the market knows the date and the size of locked stock, so you often see an overhang building, with the price drifting weaker and short interest rising into expiry, especially when locked shares dwarf the existing float. As a banker I manage that proactively. I gauge which holders actually intend to sell and roughly how much. Rather than let everyone hit the bid at once, I might arrange an orderly, marketed sell-down or an accelerated block at expiry so supply is placed with real buyers instead of dumped on screen. Sometimes we stagger releases or, if the stock is strong and demand is there, the underwriters waive the lock-up early to let a clean block clear. The key is signaling to the market in advance so the overhang is absorbed in a controlled way rather than as a disorderly air pocket.$x$),
(1909, NULL, 'primary', $x$Capital Markets$x$, $x$Underpricing And Money Left$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$IPOs often pop on day one. Quantify money left on the table for a deal that pops, and explain why issuers tolerate underpricing rather than treating it as a banker failure.$x$, $x$["Money left = pop x primary shares sold", "First-day return as underpricing proxy", "Dilution cost to selling holders", "Asymmetric information / winner's curse rationale", "Cascade and momentum benefits", "Signaling and aftermarket support", "Trade-off vs failed / broken deal risk"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Money left on the table is roughly the first-day price gain times the number of shares sold in the offering. If a company sells 20 million primary shares at 25 dollars and it closes its first day at 31, that is a 6 dollar pop on 20 million shares, so about 120 million dollars the issuer could in theory have raised at the higher price - real dilution borne by the company and selling holders. Issuers tolerate it for a few reasons. Some underpricing is rational compensation for the winner's curse: informed investors only commit if they expect a discount, so a deal priced flat to fair value risks under-subscription and a broken trade below issue. A clean pop also builds momentum, draws in coverage and aftermarket demand, supports later follow-ons or lock-up sell-downs, and leaves a positive taste for the accounts you want as long-term holders. The honest tension is that a banker can hide a weak deal behind a pop, so the goal is a healthy first-day gain - not an eye-watering double that screams the range was set far too low.$x$),
(1910, NULL, 'primary', $x$Capital Markets$x$, $x$Rights Issue Mechanics$x$, 'standard', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$A listed company wants to raise equity via a deeply discounted rights issue. Walk through the mechanics, why the discount is large, and how you would calculate the theoretical ex-rights price.$x$, $x$["Pro-rata offer to existing holders", "Subscription ratio and discounted price", "TERP as a weighted average", "Deep discount buffers risk over offer period", "Nil-paid rights are tradable", "Value-neutral if you take up or sell", "Underwriting / standby backstop"]$x$::jsonb, $x$A rights issue offers new shares pro rata to existing shareholders at a set price, with a ratio like one new share for every four held. The headline discount looks dramatic - often thirty to forty percent or more - but that is largely optics: because every holder can buy at the discount, the economic dilution is cushioned, and the deep discount mainly buys a margin of safety so the offer stays in the money over the multi-week subscription period and reduces how much the deal needs to be underwritten. I compute the theoretical ex-rights price, TERP, as a weighted average of the existing shares at the current price and the new shares at the issue price. So with four shares at 100 plus one new share at 60, that is 460 over 5, a TERP of 92. A holder who takes up their rights is value-neutral; one who does not can sell the nil-paid rights in the market to capture roughly the difference between TERP and the issue price, which compensates them for the dilution. The deal is typically underwritten or backstopped so the company is certain to get its money even if take-up is weak.$x$),
(1911, NULL, 'primary', $x$Capital Markets$x$, $x$Secondary Block Trade Risk$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$A private-equity holder wants to sell a large stake in a listed company via an overnight block. Walk through how the trade is executed and where the risk sits for the bank.$x$, $x$["Bought deal / risk trade vs agency bookbuild", "Bank buys block at discount to last", "Overnight accelerated placement to institutions", "Bank holds inventory and price risk", "Re-offer spread is the compensation", "Sizing vs ADV and market absorption", "Competitive bid compresses the discount"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Two main routes. In an agency or best-efforts trade the bank runs an accelerated bookbuild overnight, sounding out institutions and pricing only once it knows demand, so the seller carries placement risk but pays a thinner fee. In a bought deal or risk trade the bank buys the entire block from the seller at a fixed discount to the last close and then resells it - that gives the seller certainty of execution and price, but the bank now owns the inventory. That is where the risk sits: the desk is long a large position and must place it overnight with institutions at a re-offer price above its purchase price, and the spread between the two is its compensation. If demand is soft or the market gaps down before it clears, the bank wears the loss, and it may struggle to hedge if single-stock futures or stock borrow are thin. Sizing against average daily volume is critical - a block that is many days of ADV is hard to absorb and forces a deeper discount. Competition is the squeeze: in a bake-off the seller plays banks against each other, compressing the discount and the bank's cushion, so disciplined risk pricing matters.$x$),
(1912, NULL, 'primary', $x$Capital Markets$x$, $x$Direct Listing vs SPAC$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$A late-stage company is weighing a traditional IPO, a direct listing, and a SPAC merger. Compare the three on capital raised, price discovery, dilution and cost, and say when each fits.$x$, $x$["IPO raises primary capital via underwritten book", "Direct listing: no new capital traditionally / no lock-up", "Reference price vs order-driven open", "SPAC offers speed, negotiated price, forward projections", "SPAC redemptions and sponsor promote dilution", "Underpricing cost in IPO vs auction in direct listing", "Fit by capital need and market window"]$x$::jsonb, $x$A traditional IPO sells primary shares through an underwritten, book-built process: it raises capital, but you accept underpricing, an underwriting fee and a lock-up, and bankers set the range. A direct listing floats existing shares onto the exchange with no underwritten block - classically no capital raised, though reference-price mechanics now allow a primary raise - so there is no IPO discount and usually no lock-up, and price is set by an order-driven opening auction not allocated by banks. It suits a well-known, cash-rich company that wants liquidity and price discovery without dilution. A SPAC merges the company into a listed cash shell: it offers speed, a valuation negotiated with the sponsor, and the ability to market forward projections, useful for story-heavy or pre-revenue names. The catch is dilution from the sponsor promote and warrants, plus redemption risk - if holders redeem, delivered cash can fall well short of the trust. So I pick by need: IPO for fresh capital and a broad book, direct listing mainly for liquidity, and a SPAC when speed, a negotiated valuation or projections outweigh the dilution and overhang.$x$),
(1913, NULL, 'primary', $x$Capital Markets$x$, $x$IG New-Issue Process$x$, 'core', 3, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$Walk me through the mechanics of a benchmark investment-grade bond deal from the morning announcement to pricing. What do initial price thoughts, guidance, and the launch level mean, and how does the order book drive the spread tighter?$x$, $x$["Announce on the wire with IPTs / initial price thoughts", "Bookbuild intraday, single day for IG", "Guidance, then launch and set size", "Spread tightens as book grows / oversubscription", "Allocations skewed to real-money holders", "Spread to on-the-run Treasury benchmark", "Print, free to trade, watch the break"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Most high-grade deals are same-day. In the morning we announce on the wire with initial price thoughts, say Treasuries plus 150 area, alongside a structure like a 10-year benchmark. Investors enter orders with limits, and as the book builds we publish guidance, maybe plus 130 the number plus or minus 5. Once the book is comfortably oversubscribed we set the size and launch at a final spread, usually the tight end, then price against the on-the-run Treasury. The whole point of the process is price discovery: a heavily oversubscribed book lets us ratchet the spread tighter from IPTs to launch, often 20 to 30 basis points on a well-received credit. We then allocate, skewing toward high-quality real-money accounts we want as holders, and the bonds go free to trade. We watch the break afterward: if it trades tighter the deal landed well; if it widens, we probably pushed pricing too far and left a bad taste for the next visit.$x$),
(1914, NULL, 'primary', $x$Capital Markets$x$, $x$New-Issue Concession$x$, 'standard', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$What is new-issue concession, and how would you estimate it for an investment-grade issuer that already has bonds trading? Why might concessions be unusually compressed in today's heavy-supply, AI-driven DCM market?$x$, $x$["Premium over secondary / fair-value curve", "Build issuer curve, interpolate to tenor", "Concession = new spread minus fair value", "Compensates investors for size and risk", "Strong demand compresses or negates it", "Record supply met by deep cash balances", "Negative concession when heavily oversubscribed"]$x$::jsonb, $x$New-issue concession is the extra spread an issuer pays over where its existing bonds trade to get a fresh deal done. To estimate it I build the issuer's secondary curve from its outstanding bonds, interpolate to the new tenor to get fair value, and the concession is simply the new-issue spread minus that fair value. So if the 10-year interpolates to plus 120 and we price at plus 130, that is roughly 10 basis points of concession. It exists because investors want compensation for absorbing size and for the risk that the new bond cheapens the curve. In the current market, even with record DCM supply on the data-center and AI capex wave, concessions have often been thin or even negative, because investors are sitting on deep cash balances and demand is so strong that books are many times covered. When a deal is that oversubscribed you can launch through the existing curve, meaning the issuer effectively pays no premium and occasionally prints at a negative concession.$x$),
(1915, NULL, 'primary', $x$Capital Markets$x$, $x$HY Covenant Packages$x$, 'standard', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$Explain the difference between incurrence and maintenance covenants. Why do high-yield bonds typically carry incurrence covenants while bank loans historically carried maintenance covenants, and what does the rise of covenant-lite leveraged loans mean for that distinction?$x$, $x$["Incurrence tested only on an action", "Maintenance tested every period regardless", "Bonds incurrence, traditional loans maintenance", "Examples: debt incurrence, RP, liens baskets", "Maintenance gives lenders early control / springing", "Cov-lite loans now mirror bond packages", "Implications for recovery and lender leverage"]$x$::jsonb, $x$A maintenance covenant is tested every quarter no matter what the company does, for example a leverage ratio that must stay below a set level, so a deteriorating borrower trips it and gives lenders a seat at the table early. An incurrence covenant only bites when the company takes a specific action, like incurring more debt, paying a dividend, or making an investment, and it must satisfy a test at that moment, but if it does nothing it never trips. High-yield bonds use incurrence covenants because bondholders are dispersed and want to restrict aggressive actions without forcing constant compliance, whereas banks historically held maintenance tests because they were concentrated, relationship lenders who wanted early warning. The big shift is that most leveraged loans are now covenant-lite, meaning they have dropped financial maintenance tests and look much more like bond packages. That erodes the old loan-versus-bond distinction, removes lenders' early tripwire, and tends to push restructurings later, which has historically pressured recoveries.$x$),
(1916, NULL, 'primary', $x$Capital Markets$x$, $x$Call Schedule And Make-Whole$x$, 'standard', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$Walk me through a typical high-yield call schedule, including the non-call period, the par-plus-half-coupon convention, the equity claw, and how a make-whole call works. Why does an issuer accept a non-call period at all?$x$, $x$["Non-call period, e.g. NC3 on 7-year", "First call at par plus half the coupon", "Premium steps down to par over time", "Equity clawback, ~35-40% during NC", "Make-whole = PV at Treasury plus spread", "Make-whole discourages early redemption", "Trade-off: lower coupon vs call flexibility"]$x$::jsonb, $x$A typical high-yield bond is callable but only after a non-call period, so a 7-year is often non-call three. The first call price is par plus half the coupon, so an 8 percent bond first calls around 104, and the premium steps down each year to par by the last couple of years. During the non-call period there is usually an equity clawback letting the issuer redeem up to 35 or 40 percent with proceeds from an equity raise at a set premium, and a make-whole that lets it call early by paying the present value of all remaining coupons and principal discounted at the relevant Treasury yield plus a spread, usually 50 basis points. That make-whole number is punitive by design, so it preserves the call protection investors paid for rather than being a cheap refinancing route. The issuer accepts the non-call because call optionality is valuable to it and investors charge for it: agreeing to protect the bondholder for a few years lowers the coupon, and the issuer still keeps the make-whole and clawback as escape hatches if an acquisition or refinancing makes early redemption worthwhile.$x$),
(1917, NULL, 'primary', $x$Capital Markets$x$, $x$Liability Management$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'US', $x$A high-yield issuer wants to address a bond maturing in 2028 ahead of the refinancing wall. Compare a cash tender offer, an exchange offer, and a consent solicitation. When would you pair a tender with a consent, and what is exit consent or covenant stripping?$x$, $x$["Tender = cash buyback, often above market", "Exchange = new notes for old, preserve cash", "Consent = amend indenture terms only", "Pair tender with consent to strip covenants", "Exit consents pressure holdouts to tender", "Voting thresholds; payment terms need each holder", "Distressed exchange / ratings and LME risk"]$x$::jsonb, $x$All three are liability-management tools. A cash tender offer buys bonds back for cash, usually at a premium to market, and is clean but consumes liquidity. An exchange offer swaps old notes for new ones, often longer-dated, pushing out the maturity without spending much cash, which is the workhorse for that 2028 wall when refinancing outright is expensive. A consent solicitation just pays holders to amend the indenture, for example to loosen covenants, without retiring the bonds. You pair a tender with a consent when you want to both cut bonds outstanding and clean up the document: tendering holders simultaneously consent to amendments. That is where exit consents, or covenant stripping, come in. Holders who tender vote to strip restrictive covenants from the bonds left behind, making the stub less attractive and pressuring holdouts to join. You must respect indenture thresholds: most covenants amend at a simple majority, but core payment terms like principal, coupon, and maturity need each affected holder's consent. A discounted exchange on a stressed credit may be flagged a distressed exchange, a default for rating purposes.$x$),
(1918, NULL, 'primary', $x$Capital Markets$x$, $x$CP And MTN Programs$x$, 'standard', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$Compare a commercial paper program with a medium-term note program as funding tools for an investment-grade corporate. How do they fit alongside benchmark bonds and a revolver, and why does CP require committed bank backstop lines?$x$, $x$["CP short-dated, under 270 days", "MTN continuous shelf, flexible tenors / sizes", "Reverse inquiry and bespoke structures on MTN", "CP cheapest funding but rollover risk", "Backstop revolver for CP liquidity risk", "Bonds for term, locked-in funding", "Ratings drive CP tiers / market access"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Commercial paper is short-term, unsecured paper usually issued under 270 days to stay exempt from registration, and it is typically the cheapest funding a high-grade name has, used to manage day-to-day working capital and bridge timing. The risk is rollover: if markets seize, you may not be able to refinance maturing paper, which is exactly why issuers keep a committed revolver as a backstop liquidity line sized to cover outstanding CP, and the agencies and investors expect that backstop. A medium-term note program is a continuously available shelf that lets the issuer tap the market opportunistically across tenors and sizes, often via reverse inquiry where an investor requests a bespoke structure, so MTNs are great for smaller, customized, or structured trades. Benchmark bonds sit at the other end: large, liquid, fixed maturities that lock in term funding. So the toolkit layers together, CP for the cheapest short money with a revolver behind it, MTNs for flexible mid-size issuance, and benchmark bonds for big term financing. Ratings matter throughout, since CP tiers gate which money-market funds can buy your paper.$x$),
(1919, NULL, 'primary', $x$Capital Markets$x$, $x$Sustainability-Linked Bonds$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$Contrast a use-of-proceeds green bond with a sustainability-linked bond. How does the SLB coupon step-up work, what is greenwashing risk, and would you expect a meaningful greenium in the current market?$x$, $x$["Green bond ring-fences proceeds to eligible projects", "SLB general proceeds, KPI / SPT targets", "Coupon step-up if SPT missed", "Step-up often small, late, weak incentive", "Greenwashing and second-party opinion", "Greenium modest and inconsistent", "Reporting, verification, framework alignment"]$x$::jsonb, $x$A green bond is a use-of-proceeds instrument: the money is ring-fenced for eligible green projects like renewables or efficient buildings, and the issuer reports on allocation and impact, but the bond's cash flows are otherwise standard. A sustainability-linked bond is structurally different. Proceeds go to general corporate purposes, but the coupon is tied to the issuer hitting key performance indicators against sustainability performance targets, for example a carbon-intensity reduction by a target date. If it misses, the coupon steps up, commonly 25 basis points. The critique is that the step-up is often small and kicks in late, sometimes near maturity, so the financial incentive can be weak and the targets unambitious, which is the greenwashing concern. That is why a credible second-party opinion and verification of the framework and KPIs really matter. On pricing, there is sometimes a greenium, a few basis points of tighter spread from dedicated ESG demand, but it is modest and inconsistent across issuers and tenors, so I would not underwrite a deal assuming a large funding saving from the label alone.$x$),
(1920, NULL, 'primary', $x$Capital Markets$x$, $x$Split Rating Execution$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$An issuer comes to market split-rated, Baa3 by Moody's but BB-plus by S&P, straddling the IG and high-yield line. How does that complicate the new issue across documentation, investor base, indices, and pricing, and how do you decide whether to run it as an IG or a HY trade?$x$, $x$["Split across IG / HY boundary, crossover", "Lower-of or middle rating conventions", "Documentation: covenant-lite IG vs HY package", "Index eligibility differs by provider rules", "Investor base: crossover buyers bridge the two", "Pricing off crossover comps, wider than pure IG", "Process choice drives covenants and marketing"]$x$::jsonb, $x$A split rating straddling the line is a classic crossover credit, and the first decision is how the market will treat it, because index providers and investors apply conventions like taking the lower of two ratings or the middle of three. With Baa3 versus BB-plus, that determines whether the bond is even index-eligible for high-grade benchmarks, which drives a big chunk of demand. The biggest practical fork is documentation: an IG-style deal is light on covenants, while a HY-style deal carries a full incurrence package with call protection and a non-call period, and you cannot easily have both, so you pick the style up front. That choice shapes who you market to: crossover accounts that buy on both sides, plus IG buyers reaching for yield and HY buyers comfortable up in quality. On pricing you reference crossover comparables rather than pure single-A names, so it prices wider than clean IG but tighter than core high yield. I would let the more conservative rating and the investor base you most want to anchor decide whether to run it IG or HY, since getting that wrong means rebuilding documentation mid-process.$x$),
(1921, NULL, 'primary', $x$Capital Markets$x$, $x$Syndicated Loan Tranches$x$, 'core', 3, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$A sponsor-owned issuer is putting in place a senior secured credit facility with a revolver, a TLA, and a TLB. Walk me through how those three tranches differ in terms of who buys them, amortization, and pricing.$x$, $x$["Revolver undrawn liquidity backstop, commitment fee plus drawn margin", "TLA bank-held amortizing pro-rata tranche, ~5yr meaningful amort", "TLB institutional buyers (CLOs, loan funds, SMAs), nominal 1% amort plus bullet", "TLB longer tenor (6-7yr), prices wider than the pro-rata", "Revolver and TLA relationship-bank driven, syndicated together", "All floating SOFR plus margin; TLB clears broadly syndicated market"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Sure - these three sit in the same senior secured credit agreement but attract very different lenders. The revolver is undrawn liquidity, a backstop banks commit so the company can draw and repay as it needs working capital; lenders earn a commitment fee on the undrawn portion plus margin when drawn. The TLA, or term loan A, is the amortizing pro-rata piece typically held by relationship banks - it amortizes meaningfully over five years or so and prices tightest because banks cross-sell other services. The TLB, term loan B, is the institutional tranche bought by CLOs, loan funds and separately managed accounts; it has a longer tenor, usually six to seven years, only nominal one percent annual amortization with a bullet at maturity, and prices wider to compensate institutional buyers. All three are floating, quoted as SOFR plus a margin. The pro-rata revolver and TLA are bank-driven and often syndicated together, while the TLB clears in the broadly syndicated institutional market, which is why arranger strategy differs by tranche.$x$),
(1922, NULL, 'primary', $x$Capital Markets$x$, $x$OID And Market Flex$x$, 'standard', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$On a broadly syndicated term loan, explain what original issue discount is, how it relates to market flex, and why an arranger might use OID rather than just moving the spread to get a deal done.$x$, $x$["OID sells loan below par, lifts effective yield above margin", "Market flex is arranger's right to adjust terms in syndication", "Flex spans price (spread), OID, and documentation/covenants", "OID is one-time yield bump vs permanently higher coupon", "Use OID when demand soft but sponsor wants to protect headline spread", "Investors price off all-in yield to maturity"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Original issue discount is when the loan is sold to investors below par - say at ninety-nine and a half rather than one hundred - so a lender funds less than face but is repaid the full principal, which lifts the effective yield above the stated margin. Market flex is the arranger's contractual right, agreed with the sponsor up front, to adjust terms during syndication if demand is soft; that flex can be price flex on the spread, OID flex, or documentation flex on covenants. I might reach for OID instead of widening the spread for a few reasons. OID is a one-time, par-building sweetener that raises yield without permanently increasing the issuer's coupon cost, so the company keeps a lower headline margin for the life of the loan. It is also a cleaner lever when the spread is near a level the sponsor wants to protect, and it directly addresses secondary-market concerns since investors care about the all-in yield to maturity. So OID tunes execution while preserving the optics and ongoing cost of the coupon.$x$),
(1923, NULL, 'primary', $x$Capital Markets$x$, $x$Soft Call Protection$x$, 'standard', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$A TLB investor asks about call protection. Explain what soft call means on a leveraged loan, why it exists, and how it differs from the call protection you would see on a high-yield bond.$x$, $x$["Soft call is a 101 premium on repricing or refinancing lower", "Typically a six-month 101 window", "Protects against quick repricing to a lower spread", "Loans otherwise par-callable and freely prepayable", "Bonds use hard call: multi-year no-call then declining schedule or make-whole", "Soft call narrow (repricing only); amort and cash sweeps carved out"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Soft call on a term loan B is a prepayment premium - almost always one hundred and one - that the borrower pays if it refinances or reprices the loan at a lower spread within a defined window, typically the first six months. It exists because loans are otherwise par-callable and prepayable at any time, so without protection a sponsor could reprice tighter the moment the market rallies, leaving institutional investors with reinvestment risk and a lower yield than they underwrote. The one percent premium compensates them for that. The contrast with high yield is sharp. A bond usually has hard call protection - a multi-year no-call period followed by a declining call schedule at fixed premiums - so the issuer simply cannot redeem early without paying up or doing a make-whole. Loan soft call is narrower: it only bites on a repricing or refinancing for spread reduction, it is short-dated, and ordinary amortization or excess-cash sweeps are usually carved out. So loans trade flexibility for the borrower against much lighter investor protection than bonds.$x$),
(1924, NULL, 'primary', $x$Capital Markets$x$, $x$Certain Funds Commitment$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$You are arranging committed financing for a sponsor bidding on a public-to-private acquisition. Explain the concept of certain funds, why a seller demands it, and how the commitment papers limit the conditions you can attach to funding.$x$, $x$["Certain funds gives the target seller deal certainty equal to the equity", "SunGard / limited conditionality is the market standard", "Funding conditions narrowed to essentially closing the acquisition", "No market MAC, syndication or marketing outs at funding", "Delivered via commitment letter alongside fee and engagement letters", "Public takeover rules require financing certainty; flex lives in pricing not conditionality"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Certain funds is the principle that when a sponsor signs up to buy a target, the financing must be as committed as the equity - the buyer has to be able to fund on the closing date without the banks being able to walk for market reasons. A seller, and on a public bid the takeover rules themselves, demand it because they will not accept signing a binding sale agreement only to have financing evaporate; deal certainty is the whole point. The way we deliver it in the commitment letter is limited conditionality, often called SunGard conditionality. We strip the conditions to funding down to essentially the same conditions as closing the acquisition itself - the deal closes, the major reps are true, security is granted - and we drop the usual market MAC, syndication and marketing outs at the funding stage. So there is no out for a soft loan market. The lever we keep is flex on pricing and structure during syndication through market flex, but that affects our economics, not our obligation to fund. Conditionality is certain; price can move.$x$),
(1925, NULL, 'primary', $x$Capital Markets$x$, $x$Private Credit Tradeoff$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$A sponsor asks whether to fund a buyout with a unitranche from a direct lender or run a broadly syndicated loan today. Lay out the trade-offs you would walk them through.$x$, $x$["Private credit offers speed, execution certainty, single lender or small club", "BSL prices tighter with deeper institutional liquidity", "Private credit: no public ratings, confidential, bilaterally negotiated covenants", "Syndication carries market/flex risk vs held-to-maturity certainty", "Unitranche is one blended spread, no tranching", "Size and repricing/upsizing optionality favor BSL"]$x$::jsonb, $x$I would frame it as certainty and flexibility versus cost and liquidity. A unitranche from a direct lender gives speed and execution certainty - often a single lender or a small club, no public ratings, no syndication or flex risk, confidential terms, and a covenant package you negotiate bilaterally. With private credit now rivaling the syndicated market in scale, it frequently wins precisely on that certainty, which matters in a higher-for-longer, choppier backdrop. The cost is that you pay for it: the all-in spread on a unitranche is typically wider than a comparable broadly syndicated loan, because one lender holds the whole risk to maturity rather than distributing it. The broadly syndicated route tends to price tighter, taps deeper institutional liquidity from CLOs and loan funds, and gives the sponsor valuable repricing and upsizing optionality if markets rally. The flip side is execution risk - you are exposed to market flex and a window that can move. For very large deals BSL depth is hard to replicate; for speed, complexity, or confidentiality, private credit often wins.$x$),
(1926, NULL, 'primary', $x$Capital Markets$x$, $x$144A Reg S Placement$x$, 'standard', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$For the bond takeout of an LBO bridge, the team debates a 144A deal, a Reg S tranche, and a traditional private placement. Explain how these three distribution methods differ and what drives the choice.$x$, $x$["144A sells to QIBs under the resale exemption, US institutional", "Reg S is the offshore exemption for non-US investors", "Most deals 144A-for-life vs older registration-rights structures", "Traditional PP: small club, heavily negotiated, often insurers off NAIC", "144A offers deepest HY liquidity for a standard takeout", "Reg S often paired with 144A to widen the book across US and offshore"]$x$::jsonb, $x$These are three different ways to distribute the same debt. A 144A deal sells to qualified institutional buyers under the resale exemption - it is the workhorse for high-yield takeouts because it reaches the deepest pool of US institutional accounts with offering-memorandum disclosure rather than a full SEC registration, and most deals today are 144A-for-life rather than carrying registration rights. Reg S is the offshore exemption: it places bonds with non-US investors outside the United States, and you very often pair a 144A and Reg S tranche in the same transaction to widen the book across US and international accounts. A traditional private placement is different in character - a small club of institutions, frequently insurance companies pricing off NAIC treatment, with heavily negotiated, bespoke covenants and limited or no secondary liquidity. The choice is driven by size, speed, investor reach and how standardized you want terms: for a large bridge takeout you want 144A liquidity, often with Reg S; for a smaller, relationship, covenant-tailored issue, a private placement can fit better.$x$),
(1927, NULL, 'primary', $x$Capital Markets$x$, $x$Underwriting Risk On Commitments$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$When a bank underwrites committed LBO financing, it takes real balance-sheet risk between signing and distribution. Explain exactly where that risk sits, what a hung deal is, and the contractual tools the bank builds into the papers to protect itself.$x$, $x$["Risk is the commitment-to-distribution gap on a firm underwrite", "Hung deal: markets sell off, bank cannot clear at par and holds the paper", "Market flex lets the bank widen spread/OID and tighten docs up to caps", "Securities demand / flex-up forces the issuer to a bond at capped rates", "Bridge funds at close then rolls to higher-cost term loans if not refinanced", "Caps, fees, and flex limit but do not erase the loss versus par"]$x$::jsonb, $x$The risk lives in the window between when we sign a firm commitment and when we actually distribute the paper. On an underwrite we promise the full amount, so if credit markets gap wider after signing, we still have to fund - and we may not be able to sell the loan or bond at par. That is a hung deal: we are left holding it on balance sheet, marking it below par and tying up capital. The contractual tools all aim to shift or cap that risk. Market flex is the main one - the right to widen the spread, add or deepen OID, and tighten covenants during syndication up to agreed caps, so we can reprice into demand without breaching our commitment. On the bridge, securities demand and flex-up provisions let us force the issuer to take out the bridge with a bond and let the rate step up to a capped level over time, which both pressures a refinancing and compensates us. If nothing prints, the bridge funds at close and converts into longer-dated term loans at that cap. None of this removes the risk - caps and underwriting fees just bound the loss and pay us for warehousing it, which is why disciplined structuring and leverage at commitment matter.$x$),
(1928, NULL, 'primary', $x$Capital Markets$x$, $x$SOFR Floating Mechanics$x$, 'core', 2, 'intern', 'Global', $x$A floating-rate loan is quoted at SOFR plus 350 basis points. Explain what SOFR is, how the coupon actually gets set each period, and what happens to the borrower's cash interest if the Fed keeps rates higher for longer.$x$, $x$["SOFR = Secured Overnight Financing Rate, Treasury repo based, replaced LIBOR", "Floating coupon = reference rate plus fixed credit spread (margin)", "Rate resets each period, typically Term SOFR over 1 or 3 month tenor", "Spread fixed at issue, base rate moves with Fed policy", "Higher for longer raises base rate so cash interest rises", "Borrower bears rate risk unless hedged with a swap or cap"]$x$::jsonb, $x$So SOFR is the Secured Overnight Financing Rate - it is the benchmark that replaced LIBOR, and it reflects the cost of borrowing cash overnight collateralized by US Treasuries, so it tracks Fed policy very closely. On a loan quoted at SOFR plus 350, the all-in coupon has two pieces: a base rate that floats, plus a fixed credit spread of 350 basis points that compensates the lender for the borrower's credit risk. The spread is locked at issue, but the base rate resets each interest period - usually Term SOFR over a one or three month tenor - so the coupon is recalculated each period off wherever rates are. The practical consequence is that the borrower carries the interest rate risk. If the Fed holds rates higher for longer, the base rate stays elevated, the coupon resets upward, and cash interest expense goes up - which pressures free cash flow and coverage. That is exactly why a lot of floating-rate borrowers buy an interest rate swap or a cap to fix or limit that exposure.$x$),
(1929, NULL, 'primary', $x$Capital Markets$x$, $x$Order Book Dynamics$x$, 'standard', 3, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$On an investment-grade bond deal, the syndicate launches with initial price thoughts and the book builds to roughly four times oversubscribed. Walk me through how the order book drives where the new issue finally prices and what tightening the spread does to the book.$x$, $x$["IPTs to guidance to launch as the book builds", "Oversubscription gives leverage to tighten spread", "Move from IPTs captures new issue concession", "Price tightening causes order attrition and drops", "Final spread balances cost vs book quality and allocation", "Goal is minimal concession with stable aftermarket"]$x$::jsonb, $x$The deal starts with initial price thoughts, which are deliberately set a bit cheap to wherever the curve and comparable bonds imply, so there is a built-in new-issue concession to draw demand. As investors put in orders, the syndicate watches the book build, and a four-times oversubscribed book is the signal that there is real excess demand. That oversubscription is the leverage to tighten - so they revise to guidance and then set the launch spread inside the original thoughts, moving the price tighter and shaving the concession the issuer pays. The trade-off is that as you tighten, some accounts that only liked the bond at the wider level drop out or cut their order size, so the book deflates. Good syndicate desks tighten to the point where they still hold a well-covered, high-quality book with the right anchor investors, not just the maximum tightening the book can technically absorb. The final spread is a balance: minimize the issuer's cost of funding, but leave enough concession that the bond performs in the aftermarket rather than trading down and burning the buyers.$x$),
(1930, NULL, 'primary', $x$Capital Markets$x$, $x$Refi Wall Calendar$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$It is mid-2026 and you are advising a leveraged issuer with floating-rate debt maturing in 2028. Given the maturity wall and a higher-for-longer rate backdrop, how would you think about the timing and structure of pre-funding their refinancing, and what is the risk of waiting?$x$, $x$["2028 wall plus higher rates raises refi cost and execution risk", "Pre-fund early to avoid crowded wall and window risk", "Term out floating into fixed or extend maturities", "Weigh negative carry vs rate and spread certainty", "Watch liquidity / repricing windows and rating trajectory", "Private credit as a certainty-of-execution alternative"]$x$::jsonb, $x$My starting point is that a 2028 maturity is no longer far away in capital-markets terms - it is inside most issuers' refinancing horizon, and there is a large wall of paper that all comes due around the same time. If everyone waits, they compete for the same windows and the same investor capital, so I would push to address it early and opportunistically rather than at the last minute. Structurally, with rates higher for longer, I would look at terming out floating exposure - extending maturities and potentially fixing some of the cost - so the company is not perpetually exposed to elevated resets right as it has to refinance. The honest cost of pre-funding is negative carry: you raise new money and sit on it or run two coupons for a while, which is real. But you are buying certainty on rate, spread, and access. The risk of waiting is that a soft window, a spread widening, or a rating slip lands exactly when the maturity goes current, and refinancing options shrink. I would also keep private credit on the table, because it can deliver speed and certainty of execution even if pricing is a bit wider.$x$),
(1931, NULL, 'primary', $x$Capital Markets$x$, $x$Digital Infra ABS$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$There has been a surge in asset-backed securities tied to data centers and digital infrastructure. Explain the basics of how an ABS is structured, why tranching creates the ratings, and what makes data-center cash flows attractive but also risky as ABS collateral.$x$, $x$["ABS = pool of cash-flowing assets in a bankruptcy-remote SPV", "Tranching / subordination creates senior AAA down to equity", "Credit enhancement: overcollateralization, reserves, excess spread", "Data center collateral = long lease contracts to strong tenants", "Risk: tenant concentration, obsolescence, re-lease and power risk", "Ties to AI data-center capex supercycle funding need"]$x$::jsonb, $x$At the core, an ABS takes a pool of cash-flowing assets and moves them into a bankruptcy-remote special purpose vehicle, which then issues notes backed only by those cash flows, isolating them from the originator's credit. The key mechanic is tranching: you slice the liabilities into a senior tranche that gets paid first, mezzanine below it, and an equity or first-loss piece at the bottom. Because losses hit the bottom first, the senior tranche can carry a much higher rating than the underlying pool - that subordination, plus credit enhancement like overcollateralization, reserves, and excess spread, is what manufactures the AAA. For data centers, the appeal is that the collateral is long-dated lease and service contracts to large, creditworthy hyperscale and enterprise tenants, so the cash flows look long and contracted, which fits the AI capex supercycle that needs enormous funding. The risk is the flip side: heavy tenant concentration, technology and power obsolescence, and real re-leasing and energy-cost exposure if a facility goes dark, so the durability of those contracts and the tenant credit is what you really underwrite.$x$),
(1932, NULL, 'primary', $x$Capital Markets$x$, $x$Index Inclusion Float$x$, 'advanced', 3, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$After an IPO, management is focused on getting the stock into a major equity index. Explain how index inclusion and free float are related, why passive demand matters, and how a low free float can both help and hurt a newly public company.$x$, $x$["Index inclusion triggers passive index-fund buying", "Eligibility needs minimum free float and liquidity thresholds", "Free float = shares freely tradable ex locked-up / strategic holders", "Low float can inflate the pop but raises volatility", "Lockups and concentrated holders suppress tradable float", "Float weighting means more float can mean larger index weight"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Index inclusion matters because once a stock joins a major index, all the passive funds that track that index have to buy it, which creates a large, fairly price-insensitive source of demand and typically improves liquidity and the shareholder base. But to get in, the company has to clear eligibility rules, and free float is central to those - indices require a minimum proportion of shares that are genuinely freely tradable, plus liquidity and listing tests. Free float is the share count excluding stock locked up by insiders, sponsors, or strategic holders who are not realistically selling. That is where it cuts both ways for a newly public company. A low float right after the IPO can amplify the initial pop, because a small tradable supply meets strong demand - but that same thin float makes the stock more volatile and can actually fail or limit index eligibility, and the weighting in most indices is float-adjusted, so more free float can mean a bigger index weight and more passive buying. So as lockups roll off and float grows, the stock can become more index-relevant, not less.$x$);
